@HeathieJ
I did a vist to the UK partially deboted to Agatha. Stayed at her honeymoon hotel and visited her home. Her character shines through her home. Treasures from her archeology days, collections of beloved pottery, art left behind on the walls when her house was used for recovering naval men during the war.
I have been reading her since I was pretty young, and the librarian would save her books for me. Her bio on PBS is worth the time.

@HeathieJ
I haven’t missed any either. The short stories are actually pretty good too, especially the Poirot ones, and Miss Marple’s Thirteen Problems.
If you like those sorts of mysteries you should read Dorothy Sayers’ Lord Whimsey series—they  are amazing, I reread them every few years. Also, this is whole different bird but I’ve just started reading Michael Connelly’s novels—Bosch, etc. They are all terrific (if, occasionally, a bit far fetched).

@HeathieJ
!  I read one of the Mary Westmacotts after reading straight through all the novels under her own name (the first one of which was given to me when I was about 12 by our beloved public library's children's librarian, Myra Morales -- it was "Hallowe'en Party."  One Westmacott was enough, so I didn't read any more of those... 
Christie's autobiography is excellent, and so is "Come, Tell Me How You Live."

